          "datePublished": "2025-12-15",
          "reviewRating": {
            "@type": "Rating",
            "ratingValue": "1",
            "bestRating": "5",
            "worstRating": "1"
          },
          "reviewBody": "Based on my experience, the leadership under the Managing Director of Amethyst International School is a major letdown. The MD comes across as authoritarian rather than educationally driven, with decisions that feel out of touch with both classroom realities and student needs. There is far too much emphasis on control and appearance, and far too little on genuine learning or well-being.\n\nCommunication is poor to the point of being dismissive. Concerns raised by parents or staff seem to go nowhere, giving the strong impression that feedback is inconvenient rather than welcome. Any claims of openness or collaboration feel superficial at best.\n\nWhat stands out most is the lack of empathy and accountability at the top. Teacher morale, in my opinion, appears visibly low, and the school culture suffers as a result. Instead of inspiring trust and respect, the MD’s leadership style creates frustration and disillusionment.\n\nFor a school that markets itself as “international” and forward-thinking, the leadership feels rigid, ego-driven, and outdated. I would seriously question whether the MD’s approach aligns with the values parents expect from an institution entrusted with their children’s education.",
          "publisher": {
            "@type": "Organization",
            "name": "Yellow Slate"
          }
        },
